to calculate the mean, variable “sample” and “logical” work, since they are numeric. Varible “vec_char” and “vec_factor” don’t work, since they are not numeric. when use “as. numeric”to logical, vec_char, and vec_factor, logical and vec_factor are converted to numeric numbers, while vec_char cannot be converted.

library(tidyverse)
example_df = tibble(
x = rnorm(1000),
y = rnorm(1000),
logical = x + y > 0,  
numeric_vector = as.numeric(logical), 
factor_vector = as.factor(logical)) 
mean(example_df$x)
## [1] 0.02574989
median(example_df$x)
## [1] 0.001478981

The size of dataset is 1000, 5 The mean is 0.0257499 The median is 0.001479 The proportion of cases for which the logical vector is TRUE is 0.502

ggplot(example_df, aes(x = x, y = y, color = logical)) + geom_point()

ggsave("scatter_plot.pdf", height = 4, width = 6)
ggplot(example_df, aes(x = x, y = y, color = numeric_vector)) + geom_point()

The three color spots look similar, and they are intensive around x=0 and y=0. It seems like the plots all have positive relationship.
